    <title type="text">Online Exhibition Catalogue: Connections: Communication in Ancient
      Egypt</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/index.aspx">Connections:
      Communication in Ancient Egypt</a><br /><blockquote class="tr_bq"> <a
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Introduction/Introduction.aspx"
      title="Introduction"><img alt="Predynastic-Pot (2)"
      src="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/Images/Connections/Connections/Predynastic-Pot-%282%29.jpg"
      style="height: 241px; width: 235px;" /></a> </blockquote><blockquote
      class="tr_bq"><h3><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Introduction/Introduction.aspx"
      style="font-weight: normal;" title="Introduction">Introduction</a>
      </span></h3><span style="font-size: x-small;"> Since the very beginning of
      human evolution, communication has played a crucial role in social development. In our modern
      world, when messages are conveyed through countless routes, it is very appropriate to look back
      and understand how interaction influenced past societies.</span><br /><br
      /><span style="font-size: x-small;"> ‘Connections’ aims to explore the ways in which
      the ancient Egyptians communicated between each other and those in a wider international
      environment. The methods they used are not far removed from our own, using various verbal and
      non-verbal techniques. Contributions to this study include investigations of written
      communication, along with interaction through material culture, gestures and much more.
      ‘Connections’ hopes to provide a unique insight into the ways that the Egyptians communed with
      the deceased, the illiterate, the divine and sacred worlds, foreign countries and different
      social groups.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"> An online catalogue accompanies a physical exhibition taken from objects loaned
      to the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Birmingham">University of
      Birmingham</a> from the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eton_college">Eton
      College</a> <a
      href="http://www.nicholasreeves.com/item.aspx?category=Writing&amp;id=328">Joseph
      William Myers Collection of Egyptian antiquities</a>. These objects are among the finest
      items of Egyptian art to have been collected during the late nineteenth century. Many of them
      are small masterpieces in their own right – but those less aesthetic objects also communicated
      messages, and have not been neglected in this project...</span><br /><h3
      style="font-weight: normal;"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a class="sys_0
      sys_t170" href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/index.aspx"
      title="Projects">Essays</a></span></h3><ul><li> <span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/CGallorini.aspx"
      title="Innovation Through Interactions: A Tale of Three 'Pilgrim Flasks'">Innovation through
      Interactions: A tale of three ‘pilgrim flasks', <em>by Dr Carla
      Gallorini</em></a></span> </li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/EMillward.aspx"
      title="'Actions speak louder than words': Gestures of Communication in Ancient
      Egypt">‘Actions speak louder than words’: Gestures of Communication in Ancient Egypt,
      <em>by Emily Millward</em></a></span> </li><li> <span
      style="font-size: x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/ESimmance.aspx"
      title="Communication Through Music in Ancient Egyptian Religion">Communication Through Music
      in Ancient Egyptian Religion, <em>by Eleanor Simmance</em></a></span>
      </li><li> <span style="font-size: x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/GHeffernan.aspx"
      title="Petitions to the Divine: Communication Through Votive Offerings at Egyptian
      Shrines">Petitions to the Divine: Communication through Votive Offerings at Egyptian
      Shrines, <em>by Gabrielle Heffernan</em></a></span>
      </li><li> <span style="font-size: x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/CGraves.aspx"
      title="Intercultural Communication: Egypt and Nubia c. 2543-1076BC">Intercultural
      Communication: Egypt and Nubia c. 2543-1076BC, <em>by Carl
      Graves</em></a></span> </li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/MBommas.aspx"
      title="Blue Faience Bowls and Social Practice: New light on their use and function">Blue
      Faience Bowls and Social Practice: New light on their use and function, <em>by Dr Martin
      Bommas</em></a></span> </li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/MLuiselli.aspx"
      title="Writing – Image – Material: On Media and Communication in Ancient Egypt">Writing -
      Image - Material: On Media and Communication in Ancient Egypt, <em>by Dr Michela
      Luiselli</em></a></span> </li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/MMangum.aspx" title="The
      Lost Art of Egyptian Lithics">The Lost Art of Egyptian Lithics, <em>by Meagan
      Mangum</em></a></span> </li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/NAdderley.aspx"
      title="Scarabs: Appeals for Protection and Resurrection">Scarabs: Appeals for Protection and
      Resurrection, <em>by Dr Nicola J Adderley</em></a></span>
      </li><li> <span style="font-size: x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/SGregory.aspx"
      title="Visualizing Ideology: The message of the crowned-falcon amulets">Visualizing
      Ideology: the message of the crowned-falcon amulets, <em>by Steven R. W.
      Gregory</em></a></span> </li><li> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a class="sys_0 sys_t170"
      href="http://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/activity/connections/Essays/VPasquali.aspx"
      title="The Dead and the Living Interacting Through Text: An Inscribed Funerary Cone">The
      Dead and the Living Interacting Through Text: An Inscribed Funerary Cone, <em>by
      Valentina Pasquali</em></a></span>&nbsp;
      </li></ul></blockquote><h3>&nbsp;</h3>]]></content>
